messages.content:
I have enough evidence now: the test fails specifically on `~a`, while constant folding for `~11` is already correct. Source inspection shows the compiler’s constant-folding path uses `~e->v.i`, but the VM’s `OP_FLIP` runtime path uses unary minus. I patched that single instruction and verified `tests/bitwise.be` exits successfully and runtime `~a` now prints `-12`.

ROOT CAUSE: `/work/src/be_vm.c:746` in the `opcase(FLIP)` handler implements Berry’s bitwise flip opcode with arithmetic negation: `var_setint(dst, -a->v.i);`. That makes runtime expressions like `~a` evaluate as `-a` (`~11` becomes `-11`) instead of bitwise complement (`-12`). The compiler constant-folding implementation in `/work/src/be_code.c:609` is correct (`e->v.i = ~e->v.i`), which is why `~11` passes while `~a` fails.

LOCAL FIX: Change the runtime `OP_FLIP` integer operation from unary minus to bitwise complement:
```c
/* /work/src/be_vm.c */
opcase(FLIP): {
    bvalue *dst = RA(), *a = RKB();
    if (var_isint(a)) {
        var_setint(dst, ~a->v.i);
    } else if (var_isinstance(a)) {
        ins_unop(vm, "~", *RKB());
        reg = vm->reg;
        *RA() = *vm->top;
    } else {
        unop_error(vm, "~", a);
    }
    dispatch();
}
```

GLOBAL FIX: Avoid duplicating operator semantics between compiler constant folding and VM execution. Define each unary integer operator through a shared helper/macro/table (e.g. `be_int_unop_flip(bint x) { return ~x; }`) used by both `/work/src/be_code.c` constant folding and `/work/src/be_vm.c` opcode execution. Add regression/property tests that compare literal-folded and variable-runtime forms for every unary/binary operator, e.g. `~11 == (a=11, ~a)`, `-11 == (a=11, -a)`, and similarly for bitwise binary operators. This would catch semantic drift between compile-time optimization and runtime bytecode execution.

